{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"131af5b1-f72c-4a29-99d1-a2d95b495a9f","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01Jq9qxW1BW4HKC5Gwne5BHS","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Fixing EF Core 9 breaking changes"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_019LLZDRCDP5ZpfpayuFRxSh","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-a0b523aa24804416b09f7d23b8733d14/EfApp.csproj","old_str":"    <TargetFramework>net8.0</TargetFramework>","new_str":"    <TargetFramework>net9.0</TargetFramework>"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"edit the file at /tmp/sv-a0b523aa24804416b09f7d23b8733d14/EfApp.csproj."},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_015CVvhgutyKVfcxRzKodTKt","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-a0b523aa24804416b09f7d23b8733d14/EfApp.csproj","old_str":"    <PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.SqlServer\" Version=\"8.0.0\" />\n    <PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.Design\" Version=\"8.0.0\" PrivateAssets=\"all\" />","new_str":"    <PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.SqlServer\" Version=\"9.0.0\" />\n    <PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.Design\" Version=\"9.0.0\" PrivateAssets=\"all\" />"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"edit the file at /tmp/sv-a0b523aa24804416b09f7d23b8733d14/EfApp.csproj."},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01VNSSZS1N4dYuZ2rP5DWMgL","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-a0b523aa24804416b09f7d23b8733d14/MigrationRunner.cs","old_str":"    void ApplyMigrations(AppDbContext db)\n    {\n        var strategy = db.Database.CreateExecutionStrategy();\n        strategy.Execute(() =>\n        {\n            using var transaction = db.Database.BeginTransaction();\n            db.Database.Migrate();\n            transaction.Commit();\n        });\n    }","new_str":"    // EF Core 9 wraps each migration in its own transaction automatically,\n    // so calling Migrate() inside a user transaction is no longer allowed.\n    void ApplyMigrations(AppDbContext db)\n    {\n        var strategy = db.Database.CreateExecutionStrategy();\n        strategy.Execute(() =>\n        {\n            db.Database.Migrate();\n        });\n    }"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"edit the file at /tmp/sv-a0b523aa24804416b09f7d23b8733d14/MigrationRunner.cs."}],"interactionId":"1cf9f9f1-872b-4bf6-a164-3107098b1e47","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now let me analyze the code and identify all breaking changes when migrating from .NET 8 / EF Core 8 to .NET 9 / EF Core 9.\n\nThe user mentioned:\n1. The app uses Cosmos DB provider in a separate project with existing documents using \"Discriminator\" property\n2. Has synchronous Cosmos DB queries\n\nLet me identify the breaking changes:\n\n1. **TargetFramework**: `net8.0` → `net9.0`\n2. **Package versions**: `8.0.0` → `9.0.0`\n3. **`DateTime.UtcNow` in `HasData`**: In EF Core 9, `HasData` with non-constant values like `DateTime.UtcNow` generates a warning/error because seed data should be deterministic. Actually, this was already an issue in EF Core 8 too - but let me check if there's a specific breaking change here. Actually, the issue with `DateTime.UtcNow` in `HasData` is that it changes with each migration, causing unnecessary migration diffs. This isn't a new breaking change in EF9 specifically.\n\n4. **`Database.Migrate()` inside a user transaction**: In EF Core 9, `Migrate()` now wraps each migration in its own transaction, so calling it inside a user-opened transaction will throw—this is a documented breaking change.\n\n5. **Cosmos DB - Discriminator property change**: In EF Core 9, the Cosmos DB provider changed how it handles the discriminator property, which could affect existing documents that rely on the old naming convention.\n\n6. **Cosmos DB - Synchronous queries**: Synchronous Cosmos DB queries are no longer supported in EF Core 9 and will throw, so I need to switch to async alternatives throughout the codebase.\n\nNow I'm planning the migration strategy—I'll need to update the project file for the new TFM and package versions, then work through the DbContext and related files to address these breaking changes. I'm identifying the specific EF Core 9 breaking changes that apply here: the Cosmos discriminator property shift to `$type`, removal of synchronous queries on Cosmos, the transaction wrapping issue in `MigrationRunner.cs` that will now fail, and some edge cases around `DateTime.UtcNow` in seed data that might trigger new validation. I need to focus on the actual breaking changes for EF9 and apply them to the code. There are four concrete issues to address: updating the target framework and package versions to net9.0 and 9.0.0, removing transaction wrapping around `Migrate()` calls, configuring the Cosmos discriminator to preserve the \"Discriminator\" name, and converting Cosmos sync queries to async.","outputTokens":1983,"requestId":"2832:2D2899:D19968:F2D701:69EAC6A6"},"id":"d960d59a-18ee-45c3-9191-be2ae2d9d128","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:26:33.530Z","parentId":"43f9e2df-282a-47db-b168-b410459161ff"}
